  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you say goodbye to a dying loved one?",
  "response": "Saying goodbye to a dying loved one is an incredibly difficult and emotional experience. Here are some suggestions on how to approach it:\n\n1. **Express Love and Gratitude**: Let them know how much you love them and how grateful you are for the time you've shared. Simple phrases like \"I love you,\" \"Thank you for everything,\" or \"You mean the world to me\" can be very powerful.\n\n2. **Share Memories**: Talk about happy memories and experiences you've shared together. This can bring comfort to both of you and help celebrate their life.\n\n3. **Offer Reassurance**: Reassure them that it's okay to let go and that you'll be okay. You might say something like, \"It's okay to rest now,\" or \"I'll be okay, you don't need to worry about me.\"\n\n4. **Give Permission**: Sometimes, loved ones need permission to let go. You can say, \"It's okay to go when you're ready,\" or \"We'll be okay, you can go if you need to.\"\n\n5. **Say What You Need to Say**: If there are things left unsaid, now is the time to say them. Whether it's an apology, forgiveness, or just expressing your feelings, it can bring closure for both of you.\n\n6. **Be Present**: Sometimes, just being there, holding their hand, and being a source of comfort is enough. Your presence can be more meaningful than words.\n\n7. **Respect Their Wishes**: If they have expressed specific wishes about how they want to spend their final moments, try to honor those as best you can.\n\n8. **Allow for Silence**: It's okay to sit in silence together. Sometimes, words aren't necessary, and just being together can be comforting.\n\nHere's an example of what you might say:\n\n\"Mom, I love you so much. Thank you for everything you've done for me. Remember when we used to go to the beach every summer? Those are some of my favorite memories. It's okay to rest now. I'll be okay, and I want you to know that you can go whenever you're ready. I'm here with you, and I'll always carry you in my heart.\"\n\nRemember, there's no right or wrong way to say goodbye. The most important thing is to speak from your heart and let your loved one know how much they mean to you.",
